    ls: Lists the contents of a directory.
    cd: Changes the current working directory.
    pwd: Prints the current working directory.
    mkdir: Creates a new directory.
    rm: Removes a file or directory.
    cp: Copies a file from one location to another.
    mv: Moves a file from one location to another.
    cat: Concatenates and displays files.
    grep: Searches for a specific string or pattern in a file or output.
    chmod: Changes the permissions of a file or directory.
    chown: Changes the ownership of a file or directory.
    sudo: Executes a command with administrative privileges.
    apt-get: Installs or updates software packages.
    ping: Tests network connectivity by sending packets to a network host.
    top: Displays real-time system resource usage.
    ps: Displays information about running processes.
    kill: Terminates a running process.
    tar: Creates or extracts compressed archive files.
    ssh: Connects to a remote host using the secure shell protocol.
    scp: Copies files securely between hosts using the secure copy protocol.
    ifconfig - display network interface configuration
    git - a popular version control system for managing code repositories
    tar - create and extract archive files
    wget - download files from the web
    curl - transfer data to or from a server using various protocols
    scp/rsync - transfer files between servers
    ssh-keygen - generate SSH keys for secure authentication
    screen/tmux - multiplex terminal sessions to detach and reattach to sessions easily
    diff - compare two files and display differences
    find - search for files and directories based on various criteria
    sed - stream editor for filtering and transforming text
    awk - manipulate text and data files
    grep - search for a specific pattern in a file
    top/htop - display real-time system information about processes and resources
    netstat - display network connections, routing tables, and related information
    lsof - list open files and the processes using them
    iptables - configure firewall rules
    tcpdump - capture network traffic for analysis
    ping/traceroute - test network connectivity and troubleshoot network issues
    dig/nslookup - query DNS servers for information about domain names and IP addresses
    crontab - schedule and automate tasks at specific times.

